Of 12.4% of LGBQ participants, 4.1% identified themselves as lesbian/gay, 4.8% as bisexual, and 3.5% were unsure. SMY had significantly higher scores in internalizing problems (16.84 VS 13.99, 95% confidence interval [CI] 1.94–3.77, P < 0.001), externalizing problems (15.23 VS 13.51, 95% CI 0.97–2.45, P < 0.001), and total behavioral scores (55.26 VS 47.16, 95% CI 5.55–10.63, P < 0.001) than their heterosexual peers. In sexual minority subgroup analyses, all syndrome subscales were highest in the bisexual group followed by the lesbian/gay group, and the questioning group, respectively.
